4.1 Open manufacturing device
Germany and the European Union are actively participating on
Development in the implementation of the United Nation Millennium
Development Goals (MDGs). The ACP Group of States (Africa,
Caribbean and Pacific) is of great interest, since here also involved the
majority of the LDCs (Least Developed Countries). These countries are
characterized by low gross national income, high social vulnerability
(particularly from economic point of view) as well as a poor education
and health system. The LDC countries currently include the 48 least-
developed countries in the world with a significant concentration on the
African continent. With open manufacturing devices, people in these
countries shall be enabled to produce daily life products and spare parts
out of plastic by recycling locally available waste materials for the raw
material supply. This shall later on create the opportunity to develop
additional lines of production and create value.
Fig. 2 depicts the conceptual design of the open manufacturing
device. For the size of a standard TFE (twenty foot equivalent)
container, different solutions for each module (cf. Fig. 1) were designed
and their combination, e.g., with focus on reliability, degree of
automation, overall costs and usability, evaluated. The final solution
reflects the process chain of recycling and additive manufacturing for
ABS plastics. The shredder is fed with material from the roof and
delivers granular plastics material towards an extruder. Within the
extruder, plastic material is heated and plasticized trough a dice in order
to form string. Fed from a drum-like storage, the two 3D printers in the
right part manufacture new parts and products. A small personal
computer handles the required communication and acts as human-
machine interface. The computer controls the 3D printers. The
photovoltaic root top provides shadow and helps with lifted of
container to reduce the heat within the container.
4.2 Cube factory
The Cube Factory assembles a off grid production system, combining
additive manufacturing processes, material cycles and intuitive learning
tools. It features similar to the open manufacturing device flexible
manufacturing tools like 3D-Printing, plastic waste recycling system
for self-sustaining material supply and off-grid power supply by using
photovoltaic modules and a battery system. Compared to open
manufacturing device, the Cube Factors focusses mainly on transfer of
knowledge about sustainable value creation and product life cycles.
Hence, an intuitive user interface to learn, understand and creatively use
the Cube Factory capabilities has been integrated. Users with different
levels of qualification regarding manufacturing or recycling are taken
into account in the interface design. While interactively designing,
manufacturing and recycling objects, users learn the limits, potentials
and relationship of additive manufacturing and plastics recycling.
Required learning material is provided in the user interface as multi
media clips and texts. The local and global communities, for sharing
innovative ideas about value creation, are connected via internet.
The Cube Factory provides equipment to recycle old plastic parts by
shredding and extruding these into a filament. The filament is used
once more in a 3D printer. New parts can be designed on a touchscreen
and send for production to the 3D printer. For better teaching results,
a quiz-like program will be implemented on the touchscreen in order to
offer an interactive learning course.
